---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="SS Developers | Software built for real conditions" description="I build trading, fintech, and data-heavy software that stays correct when the inputs are messy and the stakes are real.">
  <section class="hero-section">
    <div class="container hero-layout">
      <div class="stack-lg">
        <div class="section-label">Open for focused engineering work</div>
        <h1 class="hero-title">I build systems that <span class="accent">hold up under real load.</span></h1>
        <p class="hero-copy">
          I work on trading infrastructure, fintech products, automation, and data integrity layers. The common requirement is the same every time: the software has to stay correct when timing, state, and human trust are all under pressure.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a href="/contact" class="button-primary">Start a project</a>
          <a href="/projects" class="button-secondary">Read the case studies</a>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-signal-list" aria-label="What I focus on">
          <div class="hero-signal">Execution flows that reconcile cleanly across multiple runtimes and user surfaces.</div>
          <div class="hero-signal">Operator tooling that exposes system state clearly instead of hiding it behind polish.</div>
          <div class="hero-signal">Architectures built around one source of truth, predictable recovery paths, and readable audits.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-visual surface-frame" aria-hidden="true">
        <img src="/images/redesign/tech-backdrop.png" alt="" class="hero-image" />
        <div class="hero-overlay"></div>

        <div class="hero-notes">
          <div class="visual-note">
            <strong>6 years in production work</strong>
            <span>Web, mobile, fintech, automation, and cross-system architecture.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="visual-note">
            <strong>20 plus shipped builds</strong>
            <span>From landing surfaces to systems where state drift costs money and trust.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-console">
          <div class="console-bar">
            <span class="console-dot red"></span>
            <span class="console-dot yellow"></span>
            <span class="console-dot green"></span>
            <span class="console-title">ss-dev / system-check.ts</span>
          </div>
          <pre class="console-body"><code><span class="code-comment">// The contract is clear before the build starts.</span>
<span class="code-key">const</span> constraints = [
  <span class="code-value">'single source of truth'</span>,
  <span class="code-value">'readable operator state'</span>,
  <span class="code-value">'recovery paths that make sense'</span>,
];

<span class="code-key">const</span> result = <span class="code-value">'software that behaves in the real world'</span>;</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container content-split">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">What I actually build</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">Proof first, then polish.</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          I am not selling a broad agency menu. The work is specific. It usually involves systems that sync across tools, teams, or platforms and break trust quickly if the data goes stale.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="manifest">
        <div class="manifest-row">
          <strong>Trading and signal infrastructure</strong>
          <p>Execution paths, reconciliation logic, dashboards, and source-of-truth layers that stay aligned across runtimes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="manifest-row">
          <strong>Fintech and trust systems</strong>
          <p>Products where contributions, payouts, balances, and auditability need to stay boringly correct.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="manifest-row">
          <strong>Operator tooling</strong>
          <p>Internal software that helps humans see the right state quickly instead of guessing through noise.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section" id="work">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">Selected work</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">Two systems that show how I think.</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Both projects deal with trust. The first depends on technical correctness across distributed parts. The second depends on financial clarity for the people using it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="feature-stack">
        <article class="feature-panel">
          <div class="feature-panel-header">
            <div class="stack-lg">
              <div class="eyeline">Trading infrastructure</div>
              <h3 class="feature-title">SMC SuperFIB</h3>
              <p class="panel-copy">
                A distributed system that keeps a Pine Script indicator, a PHP and WordPress API, MT5 expert advisors, and a React dashboard aligned around one source of truth.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="tag-row" aria-label="SuperFIB stack">
              <span class="tag">React</span>
              <span class="tag">Node.js</span>
              <span class="tag">MT5</span>
              <span class="tag">WordPress API</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <ul class="bullet-list">
            <li>Reduced drift between trading views by designing backend authority into the system from the start.</li>
            <li>Handled time normalization, staleness gates, and cross-platform parity so decisions stayed auditable.</li>
            <li>Built operator visibility into the dashboard so state could be understood without reading raw logs.</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="/projects/superfib" class="link-inline">Read the SuperFIB case study</a>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-panel">
          <div class="feature-panel-header">
            <div class="stack-lg">
              <div class="eyeline">Community finance</div>
              <h3 class="feature-title">Stokvel Society</h3>
              <p class="panel-copy">
                A fintech platform for member contributions, trust-layer ledger handling, and predictable payout flows where clarity matters as much as the interface.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="tag-row" aria-label="Stokvel stack">
              <span class="tag">Astro</span>
              <span class="tag">Fintech UX</span>
              <span class="tag">Ledger logic</span>
              <span class="tag">Reporting</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <ul class="bullet-list">
            <li>Kept the core flow readable for members while protecting the underlying accounting logic.</li>
            <li>Designed the platform around contribution visibility, trust, and predictable payout handling.</li>
            <li>Turned a community finance workflow into software that can be monitored and explained clearly.</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="/projects/stokvel" class="link-inline">Read the Stokvel Society case study</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">Architecture stance</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">I design for failure paths before I design for screenshots.</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          The visuals matter, but the real work is elsewhere. I want the system to answer the hard questions cleanly when the data is late, a dependency fails, or a human needs to understand what happened.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="principle-grid">
        <article class="principle">
          <strong>One source of truth</strong>
          <p>When several tools touch the same state, I establish authority early so the system can reconcile instead of arguing with itself.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="principle">
          <strong>Operator readability</strong>
          <p>I expose the information that matters to the person running the system, not just the person who built it.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="principle">
          <strong>Recoverable behavior</strong>
          <p>Failures should produce understandable states and reasonable next actions, not mystery or panic.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">How the work runs</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">A small process with very little theater.</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          I keep the path visible. You know what is being built, what it costs, and where the risk lives before the project starts drifting.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline">
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <em>Discovery</em>
          <strong>I clarify the problem first.</strong>
          <p>I ask what has to be correct, what can fail safely, and what constraints are non-negotiable.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <em>System map</em>
          <strong>I define the moving parts.</strong>
          <p>You get a plan, a boundary for the work, and a view of the technical choices before the build begins.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <em>Build cadence</em>
          <strong>I ship in readable increments.</strong>
          <p>Progress stays visible and the architecture stays coherent instead of being hidden in a last-minute dump.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <em>Hardening</em>
          <strong>I finish with checks that matter.</strong>
          <p>The end of the build is about stability, clarity, and operational confidence, not rushed cosmetics.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section" id="contact">
    <div class="container contact-layout">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">Work with me</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">If the system has to stay trustworthy, I am interested.</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Tell me what you are building, what state needs to stay aligned, and where the risk sits. I will tell you quickly whether I am the right fit.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="contact-stack">
        <a href="mailto:hello@ss-developers.co.za" class="contact-card">
          <small>Email</small>
          <strong>hello@ss-developers.co.za</strong>
          <p>I handle project discussions directly.</p>
        </a>
        <div class="contact-card">
          <small>Location</small>
          <strong>Cape Town, South Africa</strong>
          <p>Remote-first, with a preference for focused builds over broad retainer work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
